<div class="penelope">
  <img src="/img/welcomingcat.png" alt="Penelope the Neocities cat">
  <div class="penelope-Bubble">
    <p>Time to teach your page a trick it can do on command. In JavaScript, a named trick is called a <strong>function</strong>.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p>A function wraps up some commands and gives them a name. Defining it teaches the trick; writing the name with parentheses <strong>performs</strong> it:</p>

<pre><code class="js">function changeSky() {
  document.body.style.background = 'linear-gradient(moccasin, lavender)'
  document.body.style.minHeight = '100vh'
}

changeSky()</code></pre>

<p>A few new things are happening here:</p>

<ul class="lesson-List">
  <li><code>document.body.style</code> lets JavaScript write CSS onto an element directly &mdash; the first line repaints your background with a fresh gradient, overriding the one from your <code class="html"><%= '<style>' %></code> element. Note the spelling change: CSS names lose their dashes in JavaScript and get a capital instead, so <code class="css">min-height</code> becomes <code>minHeight</code>.</li>
  <li>The <code>minHeight</code> line stretches the body to at least <code>100vh</code> &mdash; 100% of the <em>viewport height</em>, meaning the window. Without it, the body is only as tall as your words, so on a roomy screen the gradient would run out partway down and start over. This makes the sky fill the whole window.</li>
  <li>The trick only happens when it's <em>called</em>. Delete the <code>changeSky()</code> line and the function just sits there, knowing the trick, waiting politely.</li>
</ul>

<div class="your-Turn">
  <h4><i class="fa fa-pencil" aria-hidden="true"></i> Your turn</h4>
